# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: environmental-protection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The **18th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party** was held in the Great Hall of the People, Beijing from 8 to 14 November 2012.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The National Congress is the highest organ of the party, and is stipulated to be held every five years.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The CCP Congress endorsed the amendments to the CCP constitution, membership list of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection and elected the 18th Central Committee of the CCP.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The day after the closing of the Congress, the first plenary session was held at which the Central Committee approved the composition of the Secretariat, and soon after, the members of the Politburo and its Standing Committee, the party's most powerful decision-making body.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi Jinping succeeded Hu Jintao as CCP general secretary after the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] It was followed by the 19th National Congress of the CCP in 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Due to term limits and age restrictions, seven of the nine members of the Politburo Standing Committee retired after the Congress, and the number of Politburo Standing Committee seats reduced was from nine to seven.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The seven PSC members elected after the Congress were Xi Jinping, Li Keqiang, Zhang Dejiang, Yu Zhengsheng, Liu Yunshan, Wang Qishan and Zhang Gaoli.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Five of these were identified as associates or having benefited from the patronage of former CCP general secretary Jiang Zemin, who reportedly exerted considerable influence in shaping the composition of the new Standing Committee.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Only Li Keqiang and Liu Yunshan were considered to be members of the tuanpai.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Some 2,270 delegates selected from 40 constituencies attended the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] This represented an increase of 57 delegates and two constituencies from the 17th Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 31 of these constituencies represent China's province-level jurisdictions.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Six other delegations represented Taiwan, the People's Liberation Army, Central Party organizations, Central Government Ministries and Commissions, State Owned Enterprises, and Central Banks and Financial Institutions.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The remaining three delegations are the subject of conflicting accounts.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Hong Kong and Macau may represent two delegations or one delegation or they may be treated as part of the Guangdong delegation.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Other delegations that have been identified by various sources include the Peoples Armed Police, units involved in "social management", the public service sector, workers in private enterprises, and workers in foreign and joint enterprises.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] No more than 68% of the delegates may hold leadership positions within the party.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The remaining 32% will be "grassroots" party members who hold jobs outside of the party apparatus.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The number of females increased from the previous congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Each delegation will be selected (by the province level congresses) in an election in which there are at least 15% more candidates than there are delegates to be selected.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The candidates in these elections are heavily vetted by multiple party organs.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In addition to these 2,270 delegates, an uncertain number of additional delegates, primarily retired veteran CCP leaders, will be selected.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] At the 17th National Congress there were 57 such delegates.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 18th National Congress made ecological civilization one of the country's five national development goals.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Hu repeated the goal of establishing a *xiaokang* society by 2020.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] This goal had been set by Jiang at the 16th National Congress and also previously asserted by Hu at the 17th National Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Hu instructed the PLA to update its space strategy.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Hu also stated China should "implement the military strategy of active defense for the new period, and enhance military strategic guidance as the times so require.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 18th National Congress introduced the "core socialist values" campaign.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The campaign promotes four national goals (prosperity, democracy, civility, and harmony), four social goals (freedom, equality, justice, and the rule of law), and four individual values (patriotism, dedication, integrity, and friendship).
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Since the 18th National Congress, Xi Jinping has emphasized utilizing red resources, telling red stories, and inheriting red genes.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Congress ratified changes to the CCP constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The affirmation of "socialism with Chinese Characteristics" as a "system" (*zhidu*) was written into the party constitution for the first time.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] It was widely speculated that Xi Jinping and Li Keqiang would succeed Hu Jintao and Wen Jiabao as top Politburo Standing Committee members by November 2012, and take over the Presidency and Premiership in March 2013 at the National People's Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Since 2002, all Standing Committee members had retired if they were 68 or older at the time of a party congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] As a result of this largely unspoken convention, it was expected that all other members of the outgoing standing committee would have to retire at the 18th Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] About 70% of the members of the Central Military Commission and the executive committee of the State Council would also turn over in 2012; in addition, every member of the 17th Central Committee born before 1945 relinquished their Central Committee membership at the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Congress marked the most significant leadership transition in decades.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Chinese politics prior to the 18th National Congress trended towards "collective leadership", where the paramount leader had to share power with his circle of senior leaders in the Politburo Standing Committee, particularly the Premier.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Thus ultimately the paramount leader was not expected to have the same amount of power accorded to it during the era of Mao and Deng.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The practice of governing through consensus within the Politburo Standing Committee became the norm following the 16th National Congress in 2002.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] During that Congress, the size of the Standing Committee was increased from seven members to nine, with Luo Gan and Li Changchun being added to handle the law enforcement and propaganda portfolios, respectively.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] However, these two factors led to inefficiencies in the decision-making process.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In order to improve the efficacy of the Standing Committee, the 18th National Congress was expected to end in a return to a smaller, seven-member committee.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The propaganda and public security portfolios were expected to be downgraded to the level of the Politburo.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Apart from the largely pre-ordained selection of Xi and Li for its top two positions, intense speculation mounted over who else might join the standing committee.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Two unexpected events upset the carefully balanced political equilibrium in the lead up to the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Wang Lijun incident in early 2012 no longer made former Chongqing party chief Bo Xilai a viable candidate for the PSC, and "Ferrari crash" of the son of Ling Jihua, a top aide of Hu Jintao, was said to have reduced Hu's bargaining power in the leadership selection process.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Initial speculation placed Yu Zhengsheng, Zhang Dejiang, Li Yuanchao, Wang Qishan, and Wang Yang on the new standing committee.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] However, Li Yuanchao and Wang Yang, largely seen as belonging to the 'liberal' wing of the party, were ultimately not selected.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Instead, Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli joined the standing committee.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Liu, a former Publicity Department head, took over as both the head of the party's Central Secretariat and the top official in charge of propaganda, and was seen as the most strongly conservative member in the new PSC.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Zhang, a bookish party bureaucrat known for presiding over economic growth in numerous regions, was ostensibly selected for his technocratic competence.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Apart from Xi Jinping and Li Keqiang, all the other members of the new standing committee were born in the late 1940s and therefore would need to retire at the 19th National Congress if the informally mandated retirement rules still holds in 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Li Yuanchao (born 1950) and Wang Yang (born 1955) ostensibly could still join the 19th standing committee at that time.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 18th Politburo was also named at the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Within the 17th Politburo, eleven members were born after 1945.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Of these, seven were named to the Standing Committee (see above); and the remaining three, Liu Yandong, Li Yuanchao, and Wang Yang, retained their Politburo seats.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Bo Xilai was suspended from the Politburo prior to the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] All 14 members of the 17th Politburo born prior to 1945 relinquished their Politburo membership due to having reached the mandatory retirement age of 68 at the time of the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Conversely, this also meant that all members of the 17th Politburo born after 1945 (except Bo Xilai) maintained their Politburo membership.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Since the majority of members of the 17th Politburo retired at the Congress, some fifteen seats on the 18th Politburo were to be filled by newcomers.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] By convention, the members are listed in stroke order of surnames.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Secretariat, mainly overseeing party affairs and acting as the day-to-day executive arm of the Central Committee, was led by PSC member Liu Yunshan, who also held the post of President of the Central Party School.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Liu Qibao, Zhao Leji, and Li Zhanshu earned seats on the Secretariat, as was anticipated for the heads of the Propaganda, Organization, and General Office.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Zhao Hongzhu succeeded He Yong's place on the secretariat as the top-ranked Deputy Secretary of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection.
[src:environmental-protection/18th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Departing from the previous composition of the body, Du Qinglin, outgoing United Front Department chief, who held no other post at the time (he was later elected a ceremonial vice-chair of the CPPCC in March 2013), was elevated to the Secretariat.
[src:environmental-protection/1971-swiss-referendums] Three referendums were held in Switzerland in 1971.
[src:environmental-protection/1971-swiss-referendums] The first was held on 7 February on introducing women's suffrage at the federal level, and was approved by 66% of voters.
[src:environmental-protection/1971-swiss-referendums] The second and third were held on 6 June on a constitutional amendment to introduce the human right to a non-hazardous environment and a federal resolution on federal finances.
[src:environmental-protection/1971-swiss-referendums] In the first referendum in which women were allowed to vote, both were approved by voters.
[src:environmental-protection/1987-swiss-referendums] Seven referendums were held in Switzerland in 1987.
[src:environmental-protection/1987-swiss-referendums] The last three were held on 6 December on a federal resolution on the Rail 2000 project (approved), an amendment to the federal law on health insurance (rejected) and a popular initiative "for the protection of fens - Rothenthurm Initiative" (approved).
[src:environmental-protection/1990-swiss-referendums] Ten referendums were held in Switzerland in 1990.
[src:environmental-protection/1990-swiss-referendums] The first six were held on 1 April on four popular initiatives, a federal resolution on viticulture and an amendment to the federal law on the organisation of the federal judiciary.
[src:environmental-protection/1990-swiss-referendums] The last four were held on 23 September on two popular initiatives to phase out nuclear power and to stop the construction of any new nuclear power plants, as well as on a federal resolution on the energy article in the Swiss Federal Constitution and an amendment to the federal law on road traffic.
[src:environmental-protection/1990-swiss-referendums] Whilst the nuclear power phase-out was rejected, the other three proposals were approved.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] Thirteen referendums were held in Switzerland during 1994.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] The first five were held on 20 February on federal resolutions on roadbuilding, continuing existing truck tolls and varying tolls based on engine power or mileage, as well as a popular initiative "for the protection of the alpine region from through traffic" and an amendment to the aeronautical law.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] The second set of referendums was held on 12 June on federal resolutions on an article on the Swiss Federal Constitution on the promotion of culture and a review of the procedure for naturalising young immigrants, as well as a federal law on Swiss troops in peacekeeping operations.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] Whilst the resolutions were both approved by a majority of voters, they did not receive the approval from the majority of cantons, so were rejected, as was the law on troops.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] The next two referendums were held on 25 September on abolishing price reductions on breadstuffs and an amendment to the Strafgesetzbuch and the military penal code, both of which were approved.
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] The final three referendums were held on 4 December on federal laws on health insurance and foreigners, and a popular initiative "for a healthy health insurance".
[src:environmental-protection/1994-swiss-referendums] The two laws were approved and the initiative rejected.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The **19th National Congress of the Chinese Communist Party** was held at the Great Hall of the People, Beijing, between 18 and 24 October 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 2,280 delegates represented the party's estimated 89 million members.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Preparations for the 19th National Congress began in 2016 and ended with a plenary session of the Central Committee a few days prior to the Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In 2016, local and provincial party organizations began electing delegates to the congress as well as receiving and amending party documents.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] During the congress, a new guiding ideology, labeled Xi Jinping Thought on Socialism with Chinese Characteristics for a New Era, was written into the party's constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] It marked the first time since Mao Zedong Thought that a living party leader had enshrined into the party constitution an ideology named after himself.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The congress was also notable for the consolidation of power under Xi Jinping.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 19th National Congress endorsed the membership list of the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection and elected the 19th Central Committee, which in turn approved the members of the Politburo and its Standing Committee.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Five members of the 18th Politburo Standing Committee left the body due to having reached retirement age, and five new members joined the 19th Standing Committee: Li Zhanshu, Wang Yang, Wang Huning, Zhao Leji, and Han Zheng.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The drafting process of the Report of the 18th Central Committee began in mid-to-late 2016, probably before the 6th Plenary Session.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Normal procedure is that the sitting Politburo appoints a drafting committee that is responsible for researching major topics and can establish investigative research teams.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Draft Report is sent to party groups, such as the provincial party organisation, to government institutions, the People's Liberation Army and select mass organisations while the drafting committee consults with leading specialists.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 6th Plenary Session of the 18th Central Committee, which sat 24–27 October 2016, in its communique stated that the 19th National Congress would be held in Beijing in the second half of 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The drafting process continued after the 6th Plenary Session, and by summer 2017, forums for party and non-party members in Beijing were established to review the draft report.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] At some point in the process, retired party elders are consulted.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 7th Plenary Session convened on 11 October and was in session until 14 October 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 191 CC full members and 141 CC alternate members attended the session, with CCDI members attended in a non-voting capacity.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 7th Plenary Session laid the groundworks for the 19th National Congress, and publicised the date of its convocation.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 18th Politburo put forward a motion to the 7th Plenary Session of sending three documents to the 19th National Congress; the Report of the 18th Central Committee, Work Report of the 18th Central Commission for Discipline Inspection and amendments to the CCP constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi Jinping presented the report of the 18th Central Committee while Liu Yunshan presented the amendments to the CCP constitution to the 7th Plenary Session.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Work Report of the 18th CCDI had been presented by Wang Qishan at the 8th CCDI Plenary Session on 9 October, and sent to the 7th Plenary Session for approval.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Draft Report of the 18th Central Committee was sent to more than 4,700 individuals for review, who represented various regions and departments.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Six symposiums to hear opinions and suggestions on the draft report were organised, and Xi attended them.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 7th Plenary Session approved the documents.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Three days later, on 17 October, the preparatory meeting was convened and presided over by Xi.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 2,307 of the 19th National Congress delegates attended the meeting.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] It elected 22 individuals to the Credential Committee, 243 members to the Presidium of the 19th National Congress and Liu Yunshan was elected as the Secretary-General of the 19th National Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In addition, the attendees also approved the organizational setup and tasks of the secretariat of the congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Tuo Zhen, the Deputy Head of the Publicity Department and main spokesperson for the 19th National Congress, publicised the agenda of the 19th National Congress, which had been approved by the preparatory meeting.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The election of delegates to the 19th National Congress started on 8 November 2016 and ended in June 2017, when the 18th Central Committee had approved the quota, needed qualifications and the election procedure.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The criteria of becoming a delegate became "tougher" due to the ongoing anti-corruption campaign.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The delegates are elected from 40 electoral units.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Of the 40 electoral units, 34 are divided by a defined geographical area and six units are for the central party and government.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The People's Liberation Army makes up one of the six central units and is the largest in term of delegate quota.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] One electoral unit represents the departments directly subordinate to the Central Committee and another state-owned economy.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The quote on the number of delegates can elect does not reflect population size or party size in the given region.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Rather, it reflects the political importance of the given region or subject.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] For instance, Shanghai has historically sent the highest number of delegates to the party congresses among regional electoral units.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Delegates are elected at local congresses of local party committees.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The election process is competitive up to a point, with 15% of preliminary nominees being voted off by members during the election process.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] For instance, of the delegates elected at local party congresses of the Jiangxi Provincial Committee nominated 90 people.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The quota for the Jiangxi electoral unit was 69.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In this given unit there was 30% more candidates than seats.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Once nominated, the candidates are reviewed by Central Committee through the Organization Department.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The remaining delegates will then have to stand for election at the provincial party congress, and the winners represented their electoral unit at the 19th National Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In the election of 2016–2017 99.2% of party members participated in the election process, and increase of 1.2% since the last congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 2,287 delegates were elected according to Xinhua News Agency in early October, an increase of 30 delegates since the 18th National Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] However, the number was reduced to 2,280 in an announcement on 17 October.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Of the delegates, 24.1% were women and 11.5% were ethnic minorities.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The number of delegates who represented or were active in frontline production and manufacturing (a category which includes workers, farmers, and technicians) made up 771 delegates (33.7%, an increase of 3.2% from the 18th National Congress).
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] On 18 October, Premier Li Keqiang announced the opening of the conference.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] At the opening session, General Secretary Xi Jinping gave a political report.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] He mentioned "the scientific truth of Marxism–Leninism", which he said saved China from "passivity" which resulted in a country "taking the initiative".
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi called on to "ensure our theory evolves with the times, deepening our appreciation of the objective laws" of Marxism.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Congress declared that China and the CCP entered a "new era of socialism with Chinese characteristics" at the 18th National Congress, which it said was both consistent with and significantly different from the past nearly 40 years of reform and opening up.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi stated that it is "the question of an era to which our answer must be a systematic combination of theory and practice that addresses what kind of socialism with Chinese characteristics the new era requires us to uphold and develop, and how we should go about doing it".
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi laid out a comprehensive approach to China's developmental path.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] While the speech reflected an updating of some policy issues that had been on the Party's agenda, it put forward a more concrete implementation strategy.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi stated that economic challenges must be addressed within a "five-sphere integrated of plan" that was (1) political, (2) cultural, (3) economic, (4) social, and (5) ecological.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The immediate economic task Xi described was supply-side structural reform, focusing on the reduction of excess capacity, eliminating excess homebuilding surplus, reducing debt, and decreasing costs.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi warned against complacency and described "Three Critical Battles" that required focus: de-risking, poverty alleviation, and pollution control.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 19th National Congress re-affirmed the goal of transitioning solely state-owned enterprises towards mixed (both state and private) ownership.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] "Inadequate" refers to household income share.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] With regard to China's property sector, Xi stated that "houses are for living, not for speculation." These remarks were later part of the basis for the three red lines rule.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] With regard to international relations, Xi stated that China sought to promote coordination and cooperation with the other major powers and stated that China does not seek hegemonism or expansion.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi concluded the report by stating "Theory is fundamental to Party building...
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The congress duly elected the party's leading bodies, including the Central Committee and the Central Commission for Discipline Inspection, the internal discipline organ that has come to the political foreground since 2012.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Congress ratified changes to the Constitution of the Chinese Communist Party, including the incorporation of Xi Jinping Thought.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi thus became the first leader since Deng Xiaoping to append his name into party ideology; the change also led to many international media outlets calling Xi the "most powerful leader since Mao." The Belt and Road Initiative was also added to the party constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The terms Four Confidences, Chinese Dream, new concept for development, Four Comprehensives, Xi Jinping Thought on Strengthening the Military, Community of Common Destiny, Four Consciousnesses and the Party leads everything were also added to the Party constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] In the immediate aftermath of the congress, the Central Committee formally elected the 25-member Politburo, the 7-member Politburo Standing Committee, the general secretary of the Central Committee, and a new, scaled down Central Military Commission.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] As expected, Xi Jinping duly renewed his term as general secretary of the Chinese Communist Party, the party's top position and the *de facto* top office of China.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] However, in July 2017, Sun was abruptly removed from office and then expelled from the party, upsetting the carefully calibrated balance prior to the opening of the congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Politburo Standing Committee is generally considered to be the most powerful decision-making body in China.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Since 16th National Congress in 2002, its membership selection had become largely institutionalized, with mandatory retirement of any member who has reached the age of 68 at the time of a party congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] This informal precedent was retained at the 19th Congress.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] All five of the seven members of the 18th Politburo Standing Committee who were 68 or older at the time of the congress relinquished their seats (birth year in parentheses): Zhang Dejiang (1946), Yu Zhengsheng (1945), Liu Yunshan (1947), Wang Qishan (1948) and Zhang Gaoli (1946).
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Although the retirement of four members of retirement age was not in doubt, there was speculation prior to the Congress that Wang Qishan, 69 years old at the time of the Congress, would stay on for another term as the anti-corruption chief.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Wang made a media appearance in 2016 during which he stated that he was anticipating retiring soon due to his age, though it did not reduce the speculation.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Ultimately, Wang retired from all party bodies at the congress, but became vice-president, a largely symbolic position, in 2018, signaling that he would continue to play a limited role in state affairs.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Xi and Li Keqiang renewed their terms on the Politburo Standing Committee; five new members joined, listed below in order of precedence.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The list was consistent with that released by the Hong Kong-based *South China Morning Post* on 22 October, showing that external media sources continued to have access to the last-minute deliberations of the Beijing leadership.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] According to convention, Politburo members entering the body in 2017 must be born after 1950.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Three members of the outgoing Politburo, Liu Qibao, Zhang Chunxian, and Li Yuanchao, were not elected to the incoming Politburo even though they met the relevant age requirements.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Liu and Zhang continued to hold seats in the Central Committee and were eventually given ceremonial positions with the CPPCC and NPC, respectively.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Li Yuanchao did not secure a seat on the Central Committee and retired from politics altogether.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] All members of the 18th Politburo born prior to 1950 retired without exception.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Hu Chunhua, Xu Qiliang and Sun Chunlan returned to the Politburo for a second term, while Cai Qi, who was not even part of the outgoing Central Committee, vaulted directly into the Politburo.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Taking into account Standing Committee members who were all promoted from the Politburo level, the changes represented a 60% turnover of membership between the 18th and 19th Politburo.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Out of a total of fifteen 'open' seats, at least ten of the individuals promoted to fill them were close associates of Xi.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The day-to-day executive organ of the Politburo, the Secretariat, also saw significant turnover; the Politburo members in charge of the propaganda and organization departments, and the General Office chief typically held a seat on the Secretariat.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The likely areas of purview for each secretary are listed along with their names.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] All members of the 19th Secretariat are also concurrently members of the Politburo, with the sole exception of You Quan.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The Central Committee, composed of 204 members, was elected on 24 October 2017.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Like previous congresses, the "more candidates than seats" elections method was used.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 8% of candidates were rejected by delegate vote - the same ratio from the 18th National Congress in 2012.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] Since 2007 the higher ranks of the party apparatus has seen its median age increase while retaining retirement limits.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] The 19th Central Committee showed a continuation of this trend; Lu Hao (born 1967), the youngest full member of the previous CC, remained its youngest member.
[src:environmental-protection/19th-national-congress-of-the-chinese-communist-party] 78 members of the 18th CC were named to the 19th CC, while 32 alternate members of the 18th CC were elected to full membership of the 19th CC.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Five referendums were held in Switzerland during 2005.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The first two were held on 5 June on Switzerland joining the Schengen Area and whether registered partnerships for same-sex couples should be introduced.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The third was held on 25 September on a federal resolution on extending the agreement on free movement of people to new members of the European Union, and was also approved.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The final two were held on 27 November on a popular initiative "for food from an agriculture free of genetic modification" and on a labour law related to the opening times of shops in public transport hubs.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] In a 1992 referendum Swiss voters rejected membership of the European Economic Area, which had been seen as a stepping stone on the way to membership of the European Union (EU).
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Polls consistently showed that the Swiss did not want to join the European Union, which was confirmed in a 2001 referendum where over 75% voted against membership.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The traditional Swiss policy of avoiding foreign entanglements was also shown by it not joining the United Nations until 2002.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Business and political leaders in Switzerland however were concerned over Switzerland being isolated so the Swiss government pursued a policy of bilateral agreements with the European Union.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The EU required Switzerland to join the Schengen Agreement in order that other areas of the relationship, such as trade agreements, could continue.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] In the referendum the Swiss were asked to decide whether Switzerland should become part of the Schengen and Dublin agreements.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] If the Schengen agreement was accepted then Switzerland would have to open their borders and end any systematic checks on identity at the borders by 2007.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Switzerland would become part of a passport free zone, however customs controls would remain as Switzerland was not a member of the European Union.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The agreements would also mean that Switzerland and the European Union would share information on crime and asylum applications.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The Dublin agreement would let Switzerland turn away any asylum applicants who had already claimed asylum in another signatory of the agreements.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The Swiss government estimated that this would reduce applications by about 20%.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The Swiss government and parliament approved the accession of Switzerland to the agreements in 2003 but the Swiss People's Party collected 86,000 signatures in order to force a referendum on the agreements.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The government sold the agreements as a security arrangement which had nothing to do with membership of the European Union.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] They said that Switzerland was completely surrounded by the European Union and could not solve problems on their own.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Opponents, including the Campaign for an Independent and Neutral Switzerland and the Swiss People's Party, linked the agreements to fears over immigration.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] They also said that by agreeing to these agreements the government was taking Switzerland closer to European Union membership and that the agreements would give more power to bureaucrats in Brussels.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Opinion polls before the referendum showed about 55% in favour and 35% against, with the rest undecided.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] As the referendum neared, the polls showed that support was falling, with the rejection of the European constitution in referendums in France and the Netherlands encouraging opponents of the agreements.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The results showed about 1.47 million voted in favour of the Schengen agreement which was about 55% of those who voted.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Turnout, at 55.9% of voters, was about 10% higher than usual in Swiss referendums.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Those Swiss who lived abroad were strongly in favour of joining the Schengen area, while within Switzerland German speakers in eastern Switzerland were mainly against and French speakers in western Switzerland were mainly in favour.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The government of Switzerland welcomed the results and promised not to ignore opponents of the agreements.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The European Commission also welcomed the result of the referendum and described it as an "important step" in Swiss-EU relations.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Opponents called on the government to withdraw their application for membership of the European Union.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Meanwhile, an upcoming referendum in September on extending the free movement of labour to the 10 newest members of the European Union was seen as likely to be a harder test.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Switzerland was the last republic in Europe to give women the right to vote but in this referendum the Swiss became the first in Europe to hold a referendum on increased rights for same-sex couples.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Approval in the referendum would mean that same-sex couples would be able to register their partnerships at civil register offices.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] These registered partnerships would be legally binding agreements which could only be dissolved in the courts.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Same-sex couples would get the same inheritance, pension, social security and tax rights and obligations as heterosexual couples.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] However they would not get the right to adopt or get fertility treatment.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] A leader of the campaign for the approval of registered partnerships estimated that about 5 to 10% of the population were homosexual however the government did not expect a large number of people to register their partnerships.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Registered partnerships had already been introduced in the cantons of Fribourg, Geneva, Neuchâtel and Zurich.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Parliament approved the introduction of the registered partnerships but conservatives gathered the necessary number of signatures to force a referendum.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The government's opinion was that Switzerland needed registered partnerships as the current situation gave "insufficient legal protection" for such same-sex relationships.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] Opponents including the Swiss People's Party, Evangelical People's Party and some church groups opposed the introduction of the partnerships as they wanted to keep marriage and the family as a special status.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] A poll in April showed 66% in favour and 24% against, while another in May had 67% in favour and 24% against.
[src:environmental-protection/2005-swiss-referendums] The result of the referendum had most cantons in favour of the introduction of the registered partnerships with opposition concentrated mainly in the Roman Catholic central and southern areas of Switzerland.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Due to the pressures of overconsumption, population growth and technology, the biophysical environment is being degraded, sometimes permanently.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This has been recognized, and governments have begun placing restraints on activities that cause environmental degradation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Since the 1960s, environmental movements have created more awareness of the multiple environmental problems.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] There is disagreement on the extent of the environmental impact of human activity, so protection measures are occasionally debated.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In industrial countries, voluntary environmental agreements often provide a platform for companies to be recognized for moving beyond the minimum regulatory standards and thus support the development of the best environmental practice.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] For instance, in India, Environment Improvement Trust (EIT) has been working for environmental and forest protection since 1998.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In developing countries, such as those in Latin America, these agreements are more commonly used to remedy significant levels of non-compliance with mandatory regulation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] An ecosystems approach to resource management and environmental protection aims to consider the complex interrelationships of an entire ecosystem in decision-making rather than simply responding to specific issues and challenges.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Ideally, the decision-making processes under such an approach would be a collaborative approach to planning and decision-making that involves a broad range of stakeholders across all relevant governmental departments, as well as industry representatives, environmental groups, and community.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This approach ideally supports a better exchange of information, development of conflict-resolution strategies and improved regional conservation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Religions also play an important role in the conservation of the environment: for example, the Catholic Church's *Compendium* on its social teaching states that "environmental protection cannot be assured solely on the basis of financial calculations of costs and benefits.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Many of the earth's resources are especially vulnerable because they are influenced by human impacts across different countries.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] As a result of this, many attempts are made by countries to develop agreements that are signed by multiple governments to prevent damage or manage the impacts of human activity on natural resources.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This can include agreements that impact factors such as climate, oceans, rivers and air pollution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] These international environmental agreements are sometimes legally binding documents that have legal implications when they are not followed and, at other times, are more agreements in principle or are for use as codes of conduct.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] These agreements have a long history with some multinational agreements being in place from as early as 1910 in Europe, America and Africa.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Many of the international technical agencies formed after 1945 addressed environmental themes.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] By the late 1960s, a growing environmental movement called for coordinated and institutionalized international cooperation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The landmark United Nations Conference on the Human Environment was held in Stockholm in 1972, establishing the concept of a right to a healthy environment.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It was followed by the creation of the United Nations Environment Programme later that year.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Some of the most well-known international agreements include the Kyoto Protocol of 1997 and the Paris Agreement of 2015.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] On 8 October 2021, the UN Human Rights Council passed a resolution recognizing access to a healthy and sustainable environment as a universal right.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In the resolution 48/13, the Council called on States around the world to work together, and with other partners, to implement the newly recognized right.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] On 28 July 2022, the United Nations General Assembly voted to declare the ability to live in "a clean, healthy and sustainable environment" a universal human right.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Discussion concerning environmental protection often focuses on the role of government, legislation, and law enforcement.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] However, in its broadest sense, environmental protection may be seen to be the responsibility of all the people and not simply that of government.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Decisions that impact the environment will ideally involve a broad range of stakeholders including industry, indigenous groups, environmental group and community representatives.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Gradually, environmental decision-making processes are evolving to reflect this broad base of stakeholders and are becoming more collaborative in many countries.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Many constitutions acknowledge Tanzania as having some of the greatest biodiversity of any African country.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Almost 40% of the land has been established into a network of protected areas, including several national parks.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The concerns for the natural environment include damage to ecosystems and loss of habitat resulting from population growth, expansion of subsistence agriculture, pollution, timber extraction and significant use of timber as fuel.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 1948, Serengeti has officially established the first national park for wild cats in East Africa.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Since 1983, there has been a more broad-reaching effort to manage environmental issues at a national level, through the establishment of the National Environment Management Council (NEMC) and the development of an environmental act.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Division of the biosphere is the main government body that oversees protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It does this through the formulation of policy, coordinating and monitoring environmental issues, environmental planning and policy-oriented environmental research.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The National Environment Management Council (NEMC) is an institution that was initiated when the National Environment Management Act was first introduced in year 1983.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This council has the role to advise governments and the international community on a range of environmental issues.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The National Environment Policy of 1997 acts as a framework for environmental decision making in Tanzania.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Tanzania is a signatory to a significant number of international conventions including the Rio Declaration on Development and Environment 1992 and the Convention on Biological Diversity 1996.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Environmental Management Act, 2004, is the first comprehensive legal and institutional framework to guide environmental-management decisions.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The policy tools that are parts of the act include the use of environmental-impact assessments, strategics environmental assessments, and taxation on pollution for specific industries and products.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Formal environmental protection in China House was first stimulated by the 1972 United Nations Conference on the Human Environment held in Stockholm, Sweden.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Following this, they began establishing environmental protection agencies and putting controls on some of its industrial waste.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] China was one of the first developing countries to implement a sustainable development strategy.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 1983 the State Council announced that environmental protection would be one of China's basic national policies and in 1984 the National Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA) was established.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Following severe flooding of the Yangtze River basin in 1998, NEPA was upgraded to the State Environmental Protection Agency (SEPA) meaning that environmental protection was now being implemented at a ministerial level.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2008, SEPA became known by its current name of Ministry of Environmental Protection of the People's Republic of China (MEP).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Environmental pollution and ecological degradation has resulted in economic losses for China.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2005, economic losses (mainly from air pollution) were calculated at 7.7% of China's GDP.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This grew to 10.3% by 2002 and the economic loss from water pollution (6.1%) began to exceed that caused by air pollution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] China has been one of the top performing countries in terms of GDP growth (9.64% in the past ten years).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] However, the high economic growth has put immense pressure on its environment and the environmental challenges that China faces are greater than most countries.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] All these factors contribute to climate change and habitat loss.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2022 China was ranked 160th out of 180 countries on the Environmental Performance Index due to poor air quality and high GHG emissions.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Ecological and environmental degradation in China have health related impacts; for example, if current pollution levels continue, Chinese citizens will lose 3.6 billion total life years.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Another issue is that non-transmittable diseases among Chinese, which cause at least 80% of 10.3 million annual deaths, are worsened by air pollution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Rapid growth in GDP has been China's main goal during the past three decades with a dominant development model of inefficient resource use and high pollution to achieve high GDP.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] For China to develop sustainably, environmental protection should be treated as an integral part of its economic policies.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Since around 2010 China appears to be placing a greater emphasis on environmental and ecological protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] For example, former CCP General Secretary Hu Jintao's report at the 2012 CCP National Congress added a section focusing on party policy on ecological issues.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Most importantly, Xi Jinping has suggested clearly identifiable methods to meet the ecological demands of the country.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The report at the 19th CCP National Congress isn't simply the personal thoughts from Xi Jinping, it's a product of a long process of compromise and negotiation among competing party officials and leaders.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Additionally, the Third Plenum of the CCP in 2013 included a manifesto that placed extreme emphasis on reforming management of the environment, promising to create greater transparency of those polluting, and placing environmental criteria above GDP growth for local official evaluations.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2016, it was noted that in response to pollution and oversupply, China laid off around six million workers in state-owned enterprises and spent $23 billion to cover layoffs specifically for coal and steel companies between 2016 and 2019.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] While expensive, other benefits of environmental protection have been noticed beyond impacting citizens' health.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] For example, in the long run, environmental protection has been found to generally improve job quality of migrant workers by reducing their work intensity, while increasing social security and job quality.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Different local governments in China implement different approaches to solving the issue of ecological protection, sometimes with negative consequences for the citizens.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] For example, a prefecture in the Shanxi province imposed bans, and potential legal detentions or steep fines for violations, on coal-burning by villagers.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Although the government provided free gas-heaters often the villagers were unable to afford to run them.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In Wuhan, automated surveillance technology and video is used to catch illegal fishing, and in some cities not recycling results in negative social credit points.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It is unclear in some of these instances if citizens have any potential routes for recourse.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] News in 2023 has found that the Chinese Communist Party's recent war on pollution has already brought substantial and measurable impacts, including China's particulate pollution levels dropping 42% from 2013 levels and increasing the average lifespan expectancy of citizens by an estimated 2.2 years.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Constitution of India has a number of provisions demarcating the responsibility of the Central and State governments towards Environmental Protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The state's responsibility with regard to environmental protection has been laid down under article 48-A of the constitution which stated that "The states shall endeavor to protect and improve the environment and to safeguard the forest and wildlife of the country".
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Article 21 of the constitution is a fundamental right, which states that "No person shall be deprived of his life or personal liberty except according to the procedure established by law".
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Middle Eastern countries become part of the joint Islamic environmental action, which was initiated in 2002 in Jeddah.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Under the Islamic Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, the member states join the Islamic Environment Ministers Conference in every two years, focusing on the importance of environment protection and sustainable development.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Arab countries are also awarded the title of best environment management in the Islamic world.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In August 2019, the Sultanate of Oman won the award for 2018–19 in Saudi Arabia, citing its project "Verifying the Age and Growth of Spotted Small Spots in the Northwest Coast of the Sea of Oman".
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In Russia, environmental protection is considered an integral part of national safety.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Federal Ministry of Natural Resources and Ecology is the authorized state body tasked with managing environmental protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] However, there are a lot of environmental issues in Russia.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Environmental protection has become an important task for the institutions of the European Community after the Maastricht Treaty for the European Union ratification by all of its member states.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The EU is active in the field of environmental policy, issuing directives such as those on environmental impact assessment and on access to environmental information for citizens in the member states.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 1874, an article to protect forests was introduced in the Swiss Federal Constitution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 1962, a constitutional article was introduced for the protection of nature.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The right of environmental organizations to appeal was later also included in the Federal Act on the Protection of the Environment (1985, article 55) and the Federal Act on Non-Human Gene Technology (2004, article 28).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Federal Inventory of Landscapes and Natural Monuments was introduced in 1977.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] On 21 May 2017, 58 per cent of Swiss voters accepted the new Energy Act establishing the energy strategy 2050 (energy transition) and forbidding the construction of new nuclear power plants.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Several federal popular initiative were launched to increase environmental protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The environmental protection in Switzerland is mainly based on the measures to be taken against global warming.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The pollution in Switzerland is mainly the pollution caused by vehicles and the litteration by tourists.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) has identified 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The list includes six Latin American countries: Brazil, Colombia, Ecuador, Mexico, Peru and Venezuela.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Mexico and Brazil stand out among the rest because they have the largest area, population and number of species.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] These countries represent a major concern for environmental protection because they have high rates of deforestation, ecosystems loss, pollution, and population growth.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Brazil has the largest amount of the world's tropical forests, 4,105,401 km2 (48.1% of Brazil), concentrated in the Amazon region.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Brazil is home to vast biological diversity, first among the megadiverse countries of the world, having between 15% and 20% of the 1.5 million globally described species.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The organization in charge of environment protection is the Brazilian Ministry of the Environment (in Portuguese: Ministério do Meio Ambiente, MMA).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It was first created in the year 1973 with the name Special Secretariat for the Environment (Secretaria Especial de Meio Ambiente), changing names several times, and adopting the final name in the year 1999.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2011, protected areas of the Amazon covered 2,197,485 km2 (an area larger than Greenland), with conservation units, like national parks, accounting for just over half (50.6%) and indigenous territories representing the remaining 49.4%.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] With over 200,000 different species, Mexico is home to 10–12% of the world's biodiversity, ranking first in reptile biodiversity and second in mammals—one estimate indicates that over 50% of all animal and plant species live in Mexico.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The history of environmental policy in Mexico started in the 1940s with the enactment of the Law of Conservation of Soil and Water (in Spanish: Ley de Conservación de Suelo y Agua).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Three decades later, at the beginning of the 1970s, the Law to Prevent and Control Environmental Pollution was created (Ley para Prevenir y Controlar la Contaminación Ambiental).
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In the year 1972 was the first direct response from the federal government to address eminent health effects from environmental issues.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It established the administrative organization of the Secretariat for the Improvement of the Environment (Subsecretaría para el Mejoramiento del Ambiente) in the Department of Health and Welfare.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Secretariat of Environment and Natural Resources (Secretaría del Medio Ambiente y Recursos Naturales, SEMARNAT) is Mexico's environment ministry.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In November 2000 there were 127 protected areas; currently there are 174, covering an area of 25,384,818 hectares, increasing federally protected areas from 8.6% to 12.85% of its land area.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In 2008, there was 98,487,116 ha of terrestrial protected area, covering 12.8% of the land area of Australia.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The 2002 figures of 10.1% of terrestrial area and 64,615,554 ha of protected marine area were found to poorly represent about half of Australia's 85 bioregions.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Environmental protection in Australia could be seen as starting with the formation of the first national park, Royal National Park, in 1879.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] More progressive environmental protection had it start in the 1960s and 1970s with major international programs such as the United Nations Conference on the Human Environment in 1972, the Environment Committee of the OECD in 1970, and the United Nations Environment Programme of 1972.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] These events laid the foundations by increasing public awareness and support for regulation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] These councils have since been replaced by the Australian and New Zealand Environment and Conservation Council (ANZECC) in 1991 and finally the Environment Protection and Heritage Council (EPHC) in 2001.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] At a national level, the *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the primary environmental protection legislation for the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It concerns matters of national and international environmental significance regarding flora, fauna, ecological communities and cultural heritage.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] It also has jurisdiction over any activity conducted by the Commonwealth, or affecting it, that has significant environmental impact.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] At a state level, the bulk of environmental protection issues are left to the responsibility of the state or territory.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Each state in Australia has its own environmental protection legislation and corresponding agencies.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Their jurisdiction is similar and covers point source pollution, such as from industry or commercial activities, land/water use, and waste management.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Most protected lands are managed by states and territories with state legislative acts creating different degrees and definitions of protected areas such as wilderness, national land and marine parks, state forests, and conservation areas.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] States also create regulation to limit and provide general protection from air, water, and sound pollution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] At a local level, each city or regional council has responsibility over issues not covered by state or national legislation.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This includes non-point source, or diffuse pollution, such as sediment pollution from construction sites.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Australia ranks second place on the UN 2010 Human Development Index and one of the lowest debt to GDP ratios of the developed economies.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] This could be seen as coming at the cost of the environment, with Australia being the world leader in coal exportation and species extinctions.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Some have been motivated to proclaim it is Australia's responsibility to set the example of environmental reform for the rest of the world to follow.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] At a national level, the Ministry for the Environment is responsible for environmental policy and the Department of Conservation addresses conservation issues.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] At a regional level the regional councils administer the legislation and address regional environmental issues.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Since 1970, the United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has been working to protect the environment and human health.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) is an independent executive agency of the United States federal government tasked with environmental protection matters.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] All US states have their own state-level departments of environmental protection, which may issue regulations more stringent than the federal ones.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] In January 2010, EPA Administrator Lisa P.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] As of 2019, it is unclear whether these still represent the agency's active priorities, as Jackson departed in February 2013, and the page has not been updated in the interim.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] There are numerous works of literature that contain the themes of environmental protection but some have been fundamental to its evolution.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Several pieces such as *A Sand County Almanac* by Aldo Leopold, "Tragedy of the commons" by Garrett Hardin, and *Silent Spring* by Rachel Carson have become classics due to their far reaching influences.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The conservationist and Nobel laureate Wangari Muta Maathai devoted her 2010 book Replenishing the Earth to the Green Belt Movement and the vital importance of trees in protecting the environment.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] The subject of environmental protection is present in fiction as well as non-fictional literature.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Books such as *Antarctica* and *Blockade* have environmental protection as subjects whereas *The Lorax* has become a popular metaphor for environmental protection.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] "The Limits of Trooghaft" by Desmond Stewart is a short story that provides insight into human attitudes towards animals.
[src:environmental-protection/environmental-protection] Another book called *The Martian Chronicles* by Ray Bradbury investigates issues such as bombs, wars, government control, and what effects these can have on the environment.
